

 These files demonstrate how to use the GEM message pipeline  with 
GFA  Basic 3.0.  I wanted to add this feature to a program  I  had 
written  and  I figured that others may have a need for  the  same 
kind of thing.

  The  message pipeline is a great way to  communicate  and  relay 
information between programs.  Programs that utilize the  pipeline 
allow  you  to write your own routines into  desk  accessories  to 
expand upon the program.  One program that utilizes this is  DEGAS 
Elite. Of course, you are limited to the amount of information the 
program makes available through the pipeline.

  This file won't explain the message pipeline.  The  Summer  1987 
issue  of STart magazine has an excellent article about it by  Tom 
Hudson. If you want further information, you can read that atricle 
or leave me mail here. My GEnie address is J.K.ANDREWS.

 First,  a little about the program. There should be five files in 
the archive.

ADIPTEST.GFA        GFA 3.0 Source to the program
APIDACC.GFA         GFA 3.0 Source to the accessory
APIDACC.ACC         Compiled accessory
APIDTEST.PRG        Compiled program
APID.DOC            This file

 The two source code files are commented and should help you  over 
the  rough spots.  To use this demo,  just put  the  'APIDACC.ACC' 
program  on  the root directory of your boot drive  and  boot  the 
computer.  Then,  run the program 'APIDTEST.PRG'.  The program  is 
crude  and simple.  It presents you with a one-item menu  bar.  By 
pulling  down  this  menu,  you may select  the  'Accessory  Test' 
accessory.  An  alert box will appear allowing you to  select  two 
kinds of messages.  The 'ARRAY' message will send a request to the 
program  that tells the program to send the accessory the  address 
of  an array.  The accessory receives this information and  pronts 
the  contents  of  the array.  The second option  simply  sends  a 
request to fill the last five words of the message buffer with the 
numbers 1-5. This info is received and printed on the screen.

Like I said,  it's simple and crude, but it does show that you can 
pass values and arrays to an accessory using this pipeline. 

 The message numbers you see in the listings are arbitrary ones  I 
selected.  They  have no meaning to GEM.  The programs  themselves 
look for these message numbers and act on them. In the case of the 
accessory, it sends two messages to the main program:

 &H4000            Request array address and size
 &H4001            Request values in message buffer

The  program sends reply messages with the high bit of  the  lower 
byte of the message number set. This is a good way to do things as 
described in Tom Hudson's article because it helps you keep things 
straight as to which reply goes with what message request.

 &H4080           Reply message containing array address and size
 &H4081           Reply message containing values

That's  about all there is to it.  This technique can be  expanded 
upon greatly,  and I intend to do that in my programs.  Again,  if 
you  have questions,  leave me mail at the above  mentioned  GEnie 
address.


